The paper deals with the spatial degrees of freedom of a multicell multiple access channel with multiple antennas at the users and base stations. This topic falls under the intersection of several sub-fields in computer science, including information theory (cs.IT), networking and internet architecture (cs.NI), signal processing (cs.SI), multimedia (cs.MM), and communication (cs.COM). Given the focus on channel capacity and achievable schemes, cs.IT is the most likely sub-category. However, the paper also explores interference alignment and zero forcing techniques, which are commonly used in wireless networking (cs.NI) and signal processing (cs.SI). The use of multiple antennas also suggests a potential connection to multimedia applications (cs.MM), while the overall topic of wireless communication falls under the broader category of computer communication (cs.COM).
